(7, 1, '2016-10-05 20:28:48', '2016-10-05 20:28:48', '<h2><b>Git Setup</b></h2>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Log into BitBucket and create a new repository</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go to the Repository Settings &gt; Deployment Keys, and insert the deployment key for the server.</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">If on </span><b>dev.rcms.io</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, you can go to the Framework themes repository settings and copy the deployment key from there.</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Local Setup</b>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Download the latest version of WordPress - </span><a href="https://wordpress.org/download/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://wordpress.org/download/</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unarchive the Wordpress folder into your local web server htdocs folder (XAMPP or MAMP), and rename it to your project name.</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">XAMPP - C:/xampp/htdocs/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">MAMP - /Applications/MAMP/htdocs/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go into the themes directory, and create a folder for your theme.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Clone the repository locally through SourceTree into the theme folder.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Download a copy of the RC framework child theme, and unarchive its contents into your local Git repository/theme folder.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><a href="https://bitbucket.org/rcdesigninc/rc-wordpress-framework-child-theme/downloads"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://bitbucket.org/rcdesigninc/rc-wordpress-framework-child-theme/downloads</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Commit the initial files into the repository. A message of Initial Commit works.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go to </span><a href="http://localhost/phpmyadmin"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://localhost/phpmyadmin</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and create a new database for the project</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go to </span><a href="http://localhost/projectname"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://localhost/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and go through the installation process</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Done!</span></li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<h2><b>Server setup</b></h2>\n<h3><b>Files</b></h3>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Log into the appropriate server as root - this will normally be </span><b>dev.rcms.io</b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Run the following command: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">cd /usr/share/nginx</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Download WordPress: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">wget </span><a href="http://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Uncompress the downloaded GZIP package. </span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">You will now have a folder sitting in </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">/usr/share/nginx</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> called wordpress. Rename it to your client/project: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">mv wordpress </span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go into the projects wp-content folder and remove the themes directory.</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cd </span><b><i>projectname</i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;">/wp-content</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">rm -rf themes</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Copy the Starter themes from the _starters folder</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cp -r ../../_starters/themes themes</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Rename the child theme to whatever your project is called</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cd themes</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">mv child-theme </span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go into the your project theme directory, remove the .git repository files, and re-initialize the Git repository for the project you set up during the Git Setup process.</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">cd </span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">rm -rf .git*</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git init</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git remote add origin </span><a href="mailto:git@bitbucket.org"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git@bitbucket.org</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">:rcdesigninc/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.git</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git fetch</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git checkout master</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3><b>Access/routing</b></h3>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Go to the access/hosts area: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">cd /etc/nginx/sites-available</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Copy the starter host file: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">cp _wordpress </span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Edit the file, and replace all instances of </span><b><i>projectname </i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;">with the </span><b><i>projectname</i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">nano </span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">There should be 3 locations - one for the </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">root</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">, and 2 for the </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">server_name </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">entries.</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a symbolic link from the host file you created to the sites-enabled directory</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/</span><b><i>projectname</i></b></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Run a configuration test</span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">nginx -t</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">If there are any errors, address them. Re-run the tests until you get the following message</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">nginx: the configuration file /etc/nginx/nginx.conf syntax is ok</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">nginx: configuration file /etc/nginx/nginx.conf test is successful</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Reload nginx: </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">service nginx reload</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Done!</span></li>\n</ol>\n<h3><b>Database</b></h3>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Log into the PMA database area (pma.rcms.io)</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Put in the login credentials (LastPass has them, should autofill), and change the host to the designated Database Droplet (currently db1.rcms.io)</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a new database with a </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">wp_</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> prefix (to organize the standalone WordPress installations from other sites)</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Click on your table, and then click Privileges. There should be no users listed.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a new user - use the same username as the database, the host should be </span><b>10.128.109.246</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, and generate the password from </span><a href="https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span>\n<ol>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create an entry in LastPass and store the username/password.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Grant the user All Privileges on the database.</span></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h2><b>Final</b></h2>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Once everything above is completed (Git, Local, Server setups), you can go to your project URL (most likely </span><b><i>projectname</i></b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.dev.rcms.io) and put in your database credentials you created in the last step. Then youre off to the races!</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">NEW METHOD</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a user on the server (currently TOR2) and store credentials under that clients folder in lastpass</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span> <b>adduser batemangf</b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create PHP Pool for user</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b>cd /etc/php/7.0/fpm/pool.d</b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Copy another pool .conf file, and change the following settings to the user you just created:</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">[</span><b>batemangf</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">]</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">user = </span><b>batemangf</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">group = </span><b>batemangf</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">listen = /var/run/php/php7.0-fpm-</span><b>batemangf</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.sock</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Restart the PHP process</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span><b>service php7.0-fpm restart</b></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use the </span><b>.sock</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> (above) listener when generating your vhost file</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">\n</span></li>\n</ul>', 'Setup Wordpress Site / Project on Linux Server (Digital Ocean)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'setup-wordpress-site-project-on-linux-server-digital-ocean', '', '', '2019-09-16 20:46:40', '2019-09-16 20:46:40', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220/rc-design-wiki/?p=6', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(8, 1, '2016-10-05 20:30:07', '2016-10-05 20:30:07', '<span style="font-weight: 400;">Laravel 5.2 Installation with Homestead</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Download these three software</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">GIT - </span><a href="https://git-scm.com/download/win"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://git-scm.com/download/win</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Virtual Box - </span><a href="https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Downloads"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Downloads</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Vagrant - </span><a href="https://www.vagrantup.com/downloads.html"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://www.vagrantup.com/downloads.html</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Install all three software.</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Make sure Your Computer/PC have Virtualization Technology - ENABLED</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Open GIT BASH</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Add vagrant box with with below command</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">vagrant box add laravel/homestead</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Install Homestead by cloning git repo with command</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">git clone </span><a href="https://github.com/laravel/homestead.git"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://github.com/laravel/homestead.git</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Homestead</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Run bash init.sh</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;', 'Installing Laravel With Homestead', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'installing-laravel-with-homestead', '', '', '2019-09-16 20:46:50', '2019-09-16 20:46:50', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220/rc-design-wiki/?p=8', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(11, 1, '2016-10-05 20:35:56', '2016-10-05 20:35:56', '<b>Pre-Launch Checklist</b>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b><span style="font-weight: 400;">All test copy has been removed </span></b></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Content has been checked for spelling, grammar etc. </span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">No broken links in the navigation &amp; throughout the content </span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Favicon has been added</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Enable search engine crawling - </span>ensure robots.txt is not blocking the site from being crawled</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">In WordPress, this is usually controlled in </span><b>Settings &gt; Reading &gt; Discourage search engines</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Custom 404 page has been created</span></b></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Add 301 redirects where needed</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cross-browser development has been done, IE9+, Firefox, Chrome, Safari</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">All forms are sending to the correct email addresses</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Passes W3C Validation (</span>not needed, but nice to have<span style="font-weight: 400;">)</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">All custom functionality has been tested</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Add Google Analytics - if a rebuild, use the existing ID else create a new one under our </span><a href="mailto:digitalmarketing@rcdesign.com"><span style="font-weight: 400;">digitalmarketing@rcdesign.com</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> account</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Add site to the following services:</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Webmaster tools</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sucuri Firewall</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sucuri Backups</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">UptimeRobot</span></li>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">ManageWP</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>CMS</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">OVERALL</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ensure RC theme is applied</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">hide any SEO or performance plugins from client</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ensure all fields and labels have the same typeface (including WYSIWYG)</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ensure wording on things makes sense for client</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b><span style="font-weight: 400;">CMS has been run through by at least 2 RC team members</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">CMS login information has been setup for client</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">log in to CMS under user account and ensure they can add/edit/delete everything they are supposed to</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">CAROUSEL</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ensure carousel text fields have a character count cap if needed</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">NAV UPDATES</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">move menu management into main nav (out of appearance nav)</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">hide posts, comments, contact forms, appearance, settings, users, tools, performance, SEO, framework nav items from if not needed</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">move pods under the Pages nav item</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">PAGES/POSTS/PODS</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">hide any fields or field groups that are not being used</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">rearrange field groups so they make sense/match front end ordering</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">PLUG-INS</span>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Install Wordfence Security</span></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Activate Facebook Thumb Fixer plugin</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>SEO</b>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Test with Nibbler </span><a href="http://nibbler.silktide.com/en_US"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://nibbler.silktide.com/en_US</span></a></b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Test with </span><a href="http://seositecheckup.com/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://seositecheckup.com/</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Website resolves to either www or no www (htaccess)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">All images have alt tags - images that have no proper content (its there just for show) should have a blank alt tag</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fix the </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">canonical </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">URL (www.xxx.com and www.xxx.com/index.php going to the same content means spiders pick up duplicate content) </span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use a tool like SortSite to check for broken links and other errors (including spelling)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use the &lt;title&gt; tag</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use proper H hierarchy - only one H1 tag, H1 should come before all other H tags, then H2, then H3 etc.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Main target keyword or phrase should be included in the H1 tag</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Internal links from page to page are good</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Create a relevant robots.txt file</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Set up webmaster tools, upload xmp sitemap (http://www.xml-sitemaps.com/)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Add google analytics</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Websites should no longer use Meta keywords - make sure they arent being used (as recommended by SEOMoz)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ensure all old pages are properly redirect using 301 redirects (if applicable)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Are there internal links pointing to the home page using the target phrase?</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Run through Raven to ensure maximum SEO perfomance</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b>SEO Basics (no point in listing the obvious):\n<a href="http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/other/search-engine-optimization-101/">http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/other/search-engine-optimization-101/\n</a><span style="font-weight: 400;">From my experience one of the most important parts about SEO is </span>internal linking<span style="font-weight: 400;">,</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">ive found this to be the most effective for fast SEO results.</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Meta Tags</b>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Title</span></b></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Description</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Author - </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">&lt;link rel=author href=https://plus.google.com/[YOUR PERSONAL G+ PROFILE HERE]/&gt;</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">OG (Open Graph) Tags - These tags are used when content is shared on Facebook, if they are not used, Facebook will default to the basic meta title and description.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Twitter Cards - Twitters version of Open Graph tags, when your website is shared on twitter, you can customize the title/description/image.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Accessibility</b>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Test with </span><a href="http://achecker.ca/checker/index.php"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://achecker.ca/checker/index.php</span></a></li>\n 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">All content can be accessed with the keyboard alone in a logical way</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>', 'Website Pre Launch', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'website-pre-launch', '', '', '2019-09-16 20:49:08', '2019-09-16 20:49:08', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220/rc-design-wiki/?p=11', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(13, 1, '2016-10-05 20:41:58', '2016-10-05 20:41:58', '<h2>Setup the WordPress installation</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Setup a new WordPress install. Refer to our <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xegpZTET5RdUXKbLIATzFjR8rnBs8g3sxj1vZvukj4o/edit?usp=sharing">guide</a>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Export tables from the db_wordpress database.</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Log into the RC multisite Network Admin area.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><a href="http://rcdesign.com/wp-admin/network/sites.php">http://rcdesign.com/wp-admin/network/sites.php</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n 	<li>Find the site in the listing, and click the link. The site id is in the url - ?id=X</li>\r\n 	<li>Find all tables in the db_wordpress prefixed with wp_X_, X being the site ID</li>\r\n 	<li>Make sure you export structure AND data.</li>\r\n 	<li>Export these tables.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Create the new database, and a user.</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Prefix your database with wp_. This will help organize new WP sites from other non-WP sites. ie. wp_rcdesign</li>\r\n 	<li>When creating a user, also prefix your user with wp. ie. wprcdesign\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Assign your username the host of 10.128.109.246</li>\r\n 	<li>Assign all access to the database you created</li>\r\n 	<li>Generate a password with <a href="https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/">https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/</a></li>\r\n 	<li>Store the credentials in LastPass</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Rename your Tables</h2>\r\nI would recommend having a local database set up (<a href="http://localhost/phpmyadmin">http://localhost/phpmyadmin</a>) for this.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Import your exported data from the other site into a local database. I called mine db_migration..\r\n<pre>\r\nSELECT CONCAT(\'rename table \',table_name, \' to wp_\', substr( table_name, X ), \';\')\r\nFROM information_schema.tables\r\nWHERE TABLE_NAME LIKE \'wp_Y_%\'\r\nand table_schema=\'Temp\'\r\n</pre>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>X is the count length of the existing prefix. If your site ID is a single digit, X is 6. if your site ID is a double digit, X is 7.</li>\r\n 	<li>Y is your site ID</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>DATABASE is your temporary database you created and imported this into. In my case mentioned in #1, I put db_migration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4>Example:</h4>\r\n<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/select.html">SELECT</a> <a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-functions.html#function_concat">concat</a> (\'rename table \',table_name,\' to wp_\',<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-functions.html#function_substr">substr</a>(table_name, 7),\';\')\r\n\r\nFROM information_schema.tables\r\n\r\nWHERE table_name<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-comparison-functions.html#operator_like"> like</a> \'wp_28_%\'\r\n\r\n<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/logical-operators.html#operator_and"> AND</a> table_schema=\'db_migration\'\r\n<h4>Result:</h4>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_cf7dbplugin_st to wp_cf7dbplugin_st;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_cf7dbplugin_submits to wp_cf7dbplugin_submits;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_commentmeta to wp_commentmeta;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_comments to wp_comments;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_links to wp_links;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_options to wp_options;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_podsrel to wp_podsrel;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_postmeta to wp_postmeta;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_posts to wp_posts;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_term_relationships to wp_term_relationships;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_term_taxonomy to wp_term_taxonomy;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>rename table wp_28_terms to wp_terms;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRun this as a SQL command within your database. The result will be all the sites tables ready to import into a fresh install database.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>The new WordPress Installation</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Run a new WordPress installation to create the rcdesign user. We will worry about the old users later.</li>\r\n 	<li>Export the renamed tables into the new database.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>When exporting this data, make sure the following settings are set:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>No Compression</li>\r\n 	<li>Add DROP TABLE / VIEW / PROCEDURE / FUNCTION / EVENT / TRIGGER statement</li>\r\n 	<li>Database system or older MySQL server to maximize output compatibility with: MYSQL40</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n 	<li>The wp_options table that you just imported does not have a proper wp_user_roles entry. You need to go into your wp_options table and find the entry for wp_X_user_roles, where X is your site ID. Change this option_name to wp_user_roles.</li>\r\n 	<li>The wp_options table will have the old address. If you changed the location, you will need to change the site_url and home_url entries.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>The Missing Links</h2>\r\nAt this point, you can log into the WordPress installation. Woohoo!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe WordPress starter installation folder has all of the Network Activated Plugins from the Multisite installation. You now need to go copy all of the site-specific active plugins into the new location.\r\n<h2>Plugins</h2>\r\nThe easiest way to do so is this:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Log in, and go to the Plugins screen.</li>\r\n 	<li>Youre going to see a really ugly amount of error messages saying plugins dont exist. This is your list of plugins you need to copy over.If you accidentally refresh this page before getting them all imported, you will have to write down the list from the old multisite version, or just restart the Database Import process of the new location.</li>\r\n 	<li>Log into CLI and copy over all of the plugins. Its actually pretty fast, just duplicate your first command and change the plugin name. Youll end up seeing something like this when youre done.</li>\r\n 	<li>Open the Plugins page again in a new tab. Ensure all plugins listed as missing were copied over and within the list.</li>\r\n 	<li>Activate ALL THE THINGS! These were all active on the Multisite install, so they probably should be here, too!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Themes</h2>\r\nYoull need to copy your sites theme, and probably a version (or two) of the framework theme. This piece is pretty straight forward.\r\n<h2>Uploads</h2>\r\nRemember that site ID? Were using it again! Go to /usr/share/nginx/html/wp-content/uploads/sites/X, where X is your site ID. Youre going to copy all of the contents here into your new WP installations uploads folder. Something like:\r\n\r\ncp -r ./* usr/share/nginx/projectname/wp-content/uploads/\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Install Wordfence and better search and replace</h2>\r\nInstall wordfence for better security and add <a href="mailto:webmaster@rcdesign.com">webmaster@rcdesign.com</a> into email notification option.\r\n\r\nAlso add Better Search and Replace plugin for replacing plugin directory and urls like add /uploads/sites/6 into search and replace with /uploads/ where 6 is site-id and select wp-post and wp-postmeta tables from dropdown.', 'Wordpress Site Migrating out of a Multisite', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'wordpress-site-migrating-out-of-a-multisite', '', '', '2019-09-16 20:49:19', '2019-09-16 20:49:19', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220/rc-design-wiki/?p=13', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(18, 1, '2016-10-06 17:33:57', '2016-10-06 17:33:57', '<span style="font-weight: 400;"># Install Elastic Search</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- cd into your Homestead folder</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- before \'end\' add the lines:</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">config.ssh.forward_x11 = true</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">config.vm.network "forwarded_port", guest: 9200, host: 62000</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- SSH into the vagrant box by running \'vagrant ssh\'</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- run the command \'./runAfterSSH_toInstallElasticSearch.sh\'</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- exit your vagrant SSH using the command \'exit\'</span>\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">- run \'vagrant reload\'</span>', 'Setup Laravel Elastic Search', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'setup-laravel-elastic-search', '', '', '2019-09-16 20:48:25', '2019-09-16 20:48:25', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220/rc-design-wiki/?p=18', 0, 'post', '', 0),
