(346, 1, '2018-01-16 20:22:31', '2018-01-16 20:22:31', '<pre>\r\nadd_action( \'et_builder_ready\', \'evr_initialize_divi_modules\' );\r\n\r\nfunction evr_initialize_divi_modules() {\r\n    if ( ! class_exists( \'ET_Builder_Module\' ) ) { return; }\r\n\r\n    class EVR_Builder_Module_Testimonial extends ET_Builder_Module {\r\n        function init() {\r\n            $this->name       = esc_html__( \'Testimonial\', \'evr\' );\r\n            $this->slug       = \'evr_pb_testimonial\';\r\n            $this->fb_support = true;\r\n\r\n            // ...\r\n\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n</pre>', 'Creating Custom Module In Divi', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '344-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-01-16 20:22:31', '2018-01-16 20:22:31', '', 344, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/2018/01/16/344-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(347, 1, '2018-02-20 20:31:00', '2018-02-20 20:31:00', '<h2>Setup the WordPress installation</h2>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Setup a new WordPress install. Refer to our <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xegpZTET5RdUXKbLIATzFjR8rnBs8g3sxj1vZvukj4o/edit?usp=sharing">guide</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Export tables from the db_wordpress database.</h2>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Log into the RC multisite Network Admin area.\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href="http://rcdesign.com/wp-admin/network/sites.php">http://rcdesign.com/wp-admin/network/sites.php</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li>Find the site in the listing, and click the link. The site id is in the url - ?id=X</li>\n 	<li>Find all tables in the db_wordpress prefixed with wp_X_, X being the site ID</li>\n 	<li>Make sure you export structure AND data.</li>\n 	<li>Export these tables.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Create the new database, and a user.</h2>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Prefix your database with wp_. This will help organize new WP sites from other non-WP sites. ie. wp_rcdesign</li>\n 	<li>When creating a user, also prefix your user with wp. ie. wprcdesign\n<ol>\n 	<li>Assign your username the host of 10.128.109.246</li>\n 	<li>Assign all access to the database you created</li>\n 	<li>Generate a password with <a href="https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/">https://strongpasswordgenerator.com/</a></li>\n 	<li>Store the credentials in LastPass</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Rename your Tables</h2>\nI would recommend having a local database set up (<a href="http://localhost/phpmyadmin">http://localhost/phpmyadmin</a>) for this.\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n 	<li>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Import your exported data from the other site into a local database. I called mine db_migration..\n<pre>SELECT concat (\'rename table \',table_name,\' to wp_\',substr(table_name, X),\';\')\n\nFROM information_schema.tables\n\nWHERE table_name like \'wp_Y_%\'\n\nAND table_schema=\'DATABASE\'</pre>\n<ol>\n 	<li>X is the count length of the existing prefix. If your site ID is a single digit, X is 6. if your site ID is a double digit, X is 7.</li>\n 	<li>Y is your site ID</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n 	<li>DATABASE is your temporary database you created and imported this into. In my case mentioned in #1, I put db_migration.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/select.html">SELECT</a> <a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-functions.html#function_concat">concat</a> (\'rename table \',table_name,\' to wp_\',<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-functions.html#function_substr">substr</a>(table_name, 7),\';\')\n\nFROM information_schema.tables\n\nWHERE table_name<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/string-comparison-functions.html#operator_like"> like</a> \'wp_28_%\'\n\n<a href="http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/logical-operators.html#operator_and"> AND</a> table_schema=\'db_migration\'\n<h4>Result:</h4>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_cf7dbplugin_st to wp_cf7dbplugin_st;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_cf7dbplugin_submits to wp_cf7dbplugin_submits;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_commentmeta to wp_commentmeta;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_comments to wp_comments;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_links to wp_links;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_options to wp_options;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_podsrel to wp_podsrel;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_postmeta to wp_postmeta;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_posts to wp_posts;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_term_relationships to wp_term_relationships;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_term_taxonomy to wp_term_taxonomy;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>rename table wp_28_terms to wp_terms;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n&nbsp;\n\nRun this as a SQL command within your database. The result will be all the sites tables ready to import into a fresh install database.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>The new WordPress Installation</h2>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Run a new WordPress installation to create the rcdesign user. We will worry about the old users later.</li>\n 	<li>Export the renamed tables into the new database.\n<ol>\n 	<li>When exporting this data, make sure the following settings are set:\n<ol>\n 	<li>No Compression</li>\n 	<li>Add DROP TABLE / VIEW / PROCEDURE / FUNCTION / EVENT / TRIGGER statement</li>\n 	<li>Database system or older MySQL server to maximize output compatibility with: MYSQL40</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n 	<li>The wp_options table that you just imported does not have a proper wp_user_roles entry. You need to go into your wp_options table and find the entry for wp_X_user_roles, where X is your site ID. Change this option_name to wp_user_roles.</li>\n 	<li>The wp_options table will have the old address. If you changed the location, you will need to change the site_url and home_url entries.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<h2>The Missing Links</h2>\nAt this point, you can log into the WordPress installation. Woohoo!\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe WordPress starter installation folder has all of the Network Activated Plugins from the Multisite installation. You now need to go copy all of the site-specific active plugins into the new location.\n<h2>Plugins</h2>\nThe easiest way to do so is this:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Log in, and go to the Plugins screen.</li>\n 	<li>Youre going to see a really ugly amount of error messages saying plugins dont exist. This is your list of plugins you need to copy over.If you accidentally refresh this page before getting them all imported, you will have to write down the list from the old multisite version, or just restart the Database Import process of the new location.</li>\n 	<li>Log into CLI and copy over all of the plugins. Its actually pretty fast, just duplicate your first command and change the plugin name. Youll end up seeing something like this when youre done.</li>\n 	<li>Open the Plugins page again in a new tab. Ensure all plugins listed as missing were copied over and within the list.</li>\n 	<li>Activate ALL THE THINGS! These were all active on the Multisite install, so they probably should be here, too!</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Themes</h2>\nYoull need to copy your sites theme, and probably a version (or two) of the framework theme. This piece is pretty straight forward.\n<h2>Uploads</h2>\nRemember that site ID? Were using it again! Go to /usr/share/nginx/html/wp-content/uploads/sites/X, where X is your site ID. Youre going to copy all of the contents here into your new WP installations uploads folder. Something like:\n\ncp -r ./* usr/share/nginx/projectname/wp-content/uploads/\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Install Wordfence and better search and replace</h2>\nInstall wordfence for better security and add <a href="mailto:webmaster@rcdesign.com">webmaster@rcdesign.com</a> into email notification option.\n\nAlso add Better Search and Replace plugin for replacing plugin directory and urls like add /uploads/sites/6 into search and replace with /uploads/ where 6 is site-id and select wp-post and wp-postmeta tables from dropdown.', 'Wordpress Site Migrating out of a Multisite', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '13-autosave-v1', '', '', '2018-02-20 20:31:00', '2018-02-20 20:31:00', '', 13, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/2018/02/20/13-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
