(626, 1, '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id="GenerateandLoadSSHKeysintoSourceTreewithPuTTY-Purpose">Purpose</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you set up SSH, you create a key pair that contains a private key (saved to your local computer) and a public key (uploaded to Bitbucket).&nbsp;Bitbucket uses the key pair to authenticate&nbsp;anything the associated account can access.&nbsp;This two-way&nbsp;mechanism&nbsp;prevents&nbsp;man-in-the-middle&nbsp;attacks.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This first key pair is your default SSH identity. If you need more than a default identity, you can&nbsp;<a href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/set-up-additional-ssh-keys-271943168.html">set up additional keys</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For security reasons, we recommend that you generate a new SSH key and replace the existing key on your account at least once a year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can\'t use the same key between accounts. You must create&nbsp;new keys&nbsp;for each individual Bitbucket account.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id="SetupanSSHkey-ssh1SetupSSHforGitonWindows">Set up SSH for Git on Windows</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use this section to create a default identity and SSH key when you\'re using Git on Windows. By default, the system adds keys for all identities to the&nbsp;<code>/Users/&lt;username&gt;/.ssh</code>&nbsp;directory.<a href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/set-up-an-ssh-key-728138079.html#">Collapse</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 id="SetupanSSHkey-Step1.Setupyourdefaultidentity">Step 1. Set up your default identity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li>From the&nbsp;command line, enter&nbsp;<code>ssh-keygen</code>.For Windows 7 or earlierYou can only enter&nbsp;<code>ssh-keygen</code>&nbsp;into the Git Bash window. It won\'t work in the Command prompt.The command prompts you for a file to save the key in:<code>$&nbsp;ssh-keygen<br>Generating public/private rsa key pair.<br>Enter file in which to save the key (/c/Users/emmap1/.ssh/id_rsa):</code></li><li>Press enter to accept the default key and path,&nbsp;<code>/c/Users/&lt;username&gt;/.ssh/id_rsa</code>.We recommend you keep the default key name unless you have a reason to change it.To create a key with a name or path other than the default, specify the full path to the key. For example, to create a key called&nbsp;<code>my-new-ssh-key</code>, you would enter the Windows path, shown here:<code>$&nbsp;ssh-keygen<br>Generating public/private rsa key pair.<br>Enter file in which to save the key (/c/Users/emmap1/.ssh/id_rsa):&nbsp;c:\\Users\\emmap1\\.ssh\\my-new-ssh-key</code></li><li>Enter and re-enter a passphrase when prompted.The command creates your default identity with its public and private keys. The whole interaction looks similar to&nbsp;this:<code>$&nbsp;ssh-keygen<br>Generating public/private rsa key pair.<br>Enter file in which to save the key (/c/Users/emmap1/.ssh/id_rsa):<br>Created directory \'/c/Users/emmap1/.ssh\'.<br>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):<br>Enter same passphrase again:<br>Your identification has been saved in /c/Users/emmap1/.ssh/id_rsa.<br>Your public key has been saved in /c/Users/emmap1/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.<br>The key fingerprint is: e7:94:d1:a3:02:ee:38:6e:a4:5e:26:a3:a9:f4:95:d4 emmap1@EMMA-PC</code></li><li>List the contents of&nbsp;<code>.ssh</code>&nbsp;to view the key files.You should see something like the following:<code>$&nbsp;dir .ssh<br>id_rsa id_rsa.pub</code>The command displays two files, one for the public key (for example&nbsp;<code>id_rsa.pub</code>) and one for the private key (for example,&nbsp;<code>id_rsa</code>).</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 id="SetupanSSHkey-Step2.Addthekeytothessh-agent">Step 2. Add the key to the ssh-agent</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don\'t want to type your password each time you use the key, you\'ll need to add it to the ssh-agent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li>To start the agent, run the following:<code>$&nbsp;eval $(ssh-agent)<br>Agent pid 9700</code></li><li>Enter&nbsp;<code>ssh-add</code>&nbsp;followed by the path to the private key file:<code>$&nbsp;ssh-add ~/.ssh/&lt;private_key_file&gt;</code></li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 id="SetupanSSHkey-#installpublickeyStep3.AddthepublickeytoyourBitbucketsettings">Step 3.&nbsp;Add&nbsp;the public key to your Bitbucket settings</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li>From Bitbucket, choose&nbsp;<strong>Bitbucket settings</strong>&nbsp;from your avatar in the lower left.<br>The&nbsp;<strong>Account settings</strong>&nbsp;page opens.</li><li>Click&nbsp;<strong>SSH keys</strong>.<br>If you\'ve already added keys, you\'ll see them on this page.</li><li>Open your&nbsp;<code>.ssh/id_rsa.pub</code>&nbsp;file (or whatever you named the public key file) and copy its contents.<br>You may see an email address on the last line. It doesn\'t matter whether or not you include the email address.</li><li>From Bitbucket, click&nbsp;<strong>Add key</strong>.</li><li>Enter a&nbsp;<strong>Label</strong>&nbsp;for your new key, for example,&nbsp;<code>Default public key</code>.</li><li>Paste the copied public key into the&nbsp;SSH<strong>&nbsp;Key</strong>&nbsp;field.<br></li><li>Click&nbsp;<strong>Save</strong>.<br>Bitbucket sends you an email to confirm the addition of the key.Edit an SSH keyAfter you add a key, you can edit the key\'s&nbsp;<strong>Label</strong>&nbsp;but not the key itself.&nbsp;To&nbsp;change the key\'s contents, you&nbsp;need to&nbsp;delete and re-add the key.</li><li>Return to the&nbsp;command line&nbsp;and verify your configuration and username by entering the following command:<code>$&nbsp;ssh -T&nbsp;<a href="mailto:git@bitbucket.org">git@bitbucket.org</a></code>The command message tells you which of your Bitbucket accounts can log in with that&nbsp;key.<code>conq: logged in as emmap1. You can use git or hg to connect to Bitbucket. Shell access is disabled.</code>If you get an error message with&nbsp;<code>Permission denied (publickey)</code>, check the&nbsp;<a href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/troubleshoot-ssh-issues-271943403.html">Troubleshoot SSH issues</a>&nbsp;page for&nbsp;help.</li><li> Open SourceTree and go to Tools &gt; Options. In General tab find SSH Client Configuration. Find the path to your private SSH key. For SSH Client choose OpenSSH </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that you\'ve got an SSH key set up, use the SSH URL the next time you&nbsp;<a href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/clone-a-repository-223217891.html">clone a repository</a>. If you already have a repository that you cloned over HTTPS,&nbsp;<a href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/change-the-remote-url-to-your-repository-794212774.html">change the remote URL for your repository</a>&nbsp;to its SSH URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/set-up-an-ssh-key-728138079.html">Original article</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'Set Up an SSH Key for SourceTree (Windows)', '<p>Generate and load SSH keys into SourceTree for Windows users.</p>', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'set-up-an-ssh-key-for-sourcetree-windows', '', '', '2019-10-12 22:48:17', '2019-10-12 22:48:17', '', 0, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/?p=626', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(627, 1, '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id="GenerateandLoadSSHKeysintoSourceTreewithPuTTY-Purpose">Purpose</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The goal of this article is to guide users to generate and load SSH keys into SourceTree using PuTTY.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id="GenerateandLoadSSHKeysintoSourceTreewithPuTTY-Solution">Solution</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1.&nbsp;To generate an SSH Key, select Tools &gt; Create or Import SSH Keys. This window should pop up:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://confluence.atlassian.com/sourcetreekb/files/790629663/790629656/1/1447820340893/ssh1.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Click Generate, and move the mouse randomly until a key is generated:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://confluence.atlassian.com/sourcetreekb/files/790629663/790629657/1/1447820340858/ssh2.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. A public key and a private key should appear. Save them both by clicking Save public key (save as .pub filetype), and Save private key (save as .ppk filetype):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://confluence.atlassian.com/sourcetreekb/files/790629663/790629658/1/1447820340833/ssh3.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. This is how the .pub and the .ppk files should appear in your .ssh folder, along side with some other files:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://confluence.atlassian.com/sourcetreekb/files/790629663/790629660/1/1447820340648/ssh5.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SourceTree might prompt you to load the private key. Simply load the .ppk file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Add your public key in your remote server (eg. Bitbucket).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://confluence.atlassian.com/sourcetreekb/files/790629663/790629659/1/1447820340799/ssh4.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 6. Open SourceTree and go to Tools > Options. In General tab find "SSH Client Configuration". Find the path to your private SSH key.  For SSH Client choose "OpenSSH"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, you should finally be able to use SSH as a method for git operations between local and remote.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Generate and Load SSH Keys into SourceTree with PuTTY (Windows)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '626-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '2019-09-26 14:25:58', '', 626, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/2019/09/26/626-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
