(684, 1, '2019-10-03 21:40:00', '2019-10-03 21:40:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>What it does:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adds a button to the dashboard that allows us to start the cron job manually. Will also display the server time and our time and let us know how many hours to add or subtract from our time when scheduling a cron job.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>How to use:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Install plugin</li><li>Go to Settings &gt; RC Refresh Feed to set the cron function name to call and optionally set the dashboard widget title</li><li> Go to Dashboard and click button "Refresh Feed" to run function</li><li>If it successfully runs, you\'ll get a success message "Feed updated to latest"</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Extra Notes</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>You\'ll need to know what the cron job does at the end. Creates a file? Where does it get downloaded to? Creates posts? You\'ll need to check if new ones created. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Required</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Install <a href="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/2019/09/25/github-updater/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="GitHub Updater (opens in a new tab)">GitHub Updater</a> with this plugin, so updates to the master branch get pushed to the website </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://bitbucket.org/rcdesigninc/plugin-refresh_feed_button">Get repo</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'Refresh Feed', '<p><strong>What it does:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Adds a button to the dashboard that allows us to start the cron job. Will also display the server time and our time and let us know how many hours to add or subtract from