(840, 2, '2019-10-15 15:55:25', '2019-10-15 15:55:25', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>{Form goes here}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In form:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Name of project (turn into all lowercase with no special characters and spaces become dashes). This will become:<ul><li>Name of folder on server</li><li>Database name and user and make password the default</li><li>Ftp user</li><li>Name of theme if WordPress site</li></ul></li><li>WordPress checkbox<ul><li>Copies default.christinewilson.ca WordPress installation which has all the default themes and plugins, over to the new location</li></ul></li><li>Checkbox on whether to make staging site (staging site will have htaccess password protection moved over with it)</li><li>Checkbox whether main site should be password protected (again moves htaccess file with it)</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Install new site on server', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '832-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-15 15:55:25', '2019-10-15 15:55:25', '', 832, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/832-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(841, 2, '2019-10-15 15:56:59', '2019-10-15 15:56:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>{Form goes here}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In form:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Name of project (turn into all lowercase with no special characters and spaces become dashes). This will become:<ul><li>Name of folder on server</li><li>Database name and user and make password the default</li><li>Ftp user</li><li>Name of theme if WordPress site</li></ul></li><li>WordPress checkbox<ul><li>Copies default.christinewilson.ca WordPress installation which has all the default themes and plugins, over to the new location</li><li>We\'ll create a new database for any WordPress website so it doesn\'t matter if we install plugins on default or not.. the new website will have an empty database</li></ul></li><li>Checkbox on whether to make staging site (staging site will have htaccess password protection moved over with it)</li><li>Checkbox whether main site should be password protected (again moves htaccess file with it)</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Install new site on server', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '832-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-15 15:56:59', '2019-10-15 15:56:59', '', 832, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/832-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(842, 2, '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get your input fields to render consistently across all browsers, with pixel-perfect height and vertically-centered text, you need to use both<strong>height</strong>and<strong>line-height</strong>, and avoid vertical padding. You\'ll also want to supply your own horizontal padding. Here is an example:  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>.input {\n    height: 35px;\n    padding: 0 6px;\n    line-height: 35px;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> This is tested all the way back to Internet Explorer 6 and works consistently.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://www.h3xed.com/web-development/html-input-field-consistent-cross-browser-height-and-vertical-alignment ">Original article</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'HTML Input Field Consistent Cross-Browser Height And Vertical Alignment', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'html-input-field-consistent-cross-browser-height-and-vertical-alignment', '', '', '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '', 0, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/?p=842', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(843, 2, '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get your input fields to render consistently across all browsers, with pixel-perfect height and vertically-centered text, you need to use both<strong>height</strong>and<strong>line-height</strong>, and avoid vertical padding. You\'ll also want to supply your own horizontal padding. Here is an example:  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>.input {\n    height: 35px;\n    padding: 0 6px;\n    line-height: 35px;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> This is tested all the way back to Internet Explorer 6 and works consistently.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'HTML Input Field Consistent Cross-Browser Height And Vertical Alignment', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '842-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '2019-10-15 23:40:16', '', 842, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/842-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(844, 2, '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get your input fields to render consistently across all browsers, with pixel-perfect height and vertically-centered text, you need to use both<strong>height</strong>and<strong>line-height</strong>, and avoid vertical padding. You\'ll also want to supply your own horizontal padding. Here is an example:  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>.input {\n    height: 35px;\n    padding: 0 6px;\n    line-height: 35px;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> This is tested all the way back to Internet Explorer 6 and works consistently.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://www.h3xed.com/web-development/html-input-field-consistent-cross-browser-height-and-vertical-alignment ">Original article</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'HTML Input Field Consistent Cross-Browser Height And Vertical Alignment', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '842-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '2019-10-15 23:42:58', '', 842, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/842-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(845, 2, '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Recently I went into the rats nest that is GoDaddys dashboard to setup a&nbsp;<strong>free</strong>&nbsp;email forwarding address for a side project. I found it fairly impossible. Thus leads me to this post.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is how to do this in the 2019 version of GoDaddys dashboard and Gmail. It will take you about 30 minutes. Just do all the things I say and youll get out alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->\n<h1 id="057c">Here we go</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li>Visit your GoDaddy dashboard<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://account.godaddy.com/products/" target="_blank">here</a>. Go to the <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://account.godaddy.com/products/" target="_blank">My Products</a> section.</li><li> Scroll all the way down past your domains, and expand the<strong>Additional Products</strong>section. (this took me forever to find be grateful). <br><img class="wp-image-848" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_h3BKsRTEdtiMlikSKRDPwQ.png" alt=""></li><li> Click on the <strong>Redeem</strong> button next to<strong>Email Forwarding</strong>. In the dropdown window, select the domain youd like a forwarding email address for and click the button to redeem the <strong>100 pack</strong>. <br><img class="wp-image-851" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_Bu4tYqqNB0wdxdc-ytc7Sg.png" alt=""></li><li> Scroll up to the<strong>Workspace Email</strong>section and click on<strong>Options</strong>next to the 100 pack. Dont click on Sign It it wont work if you dont have another email with GoDaddy. <br><img class="wp-image-853" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_9hV5wsf7EN6T1RhnJkol7A.png" alt=""></li><li> Click on the hilariously tiny <strong>Launch Control Center</strong> button in the top right. Yeah, GoDaddy aint interested in you doing this in the least. They want your money not your love. <br><img class="wp-image-855" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_TWM6NTEH0XTJCC-96grFcQ.png" alt=""></li><li>Check your MX Records for this domain by clicking on<strong>Tools > Server Settings</strong>. If youre MX Records are not yet setup (GoDaddy doesnt do it for you), navigate to your DNS settings for this domain and add the two MX records below. <br><img class="wp-image-857" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_c3643BvOvLdarWE3oxTZOw.png" alt=""></li><li> Now, once you are in the Launch Control Center click on<strong>Create Forward</strong>in the menu bar. <br><img class="wp-image-859" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_Kst2pZ0jHwWlrTMjc4f8AA.png" alt=""></li><li> Enter the email address you want to create for your domain, and enter in the Gmail email address you want to forward that email to. You may want to go ahead and enable the Catch All feature on this screen. <br><img class="wp-image-860" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_E-5HGv3rO5PHXTx0mMx9vw.png" alt=""></li><li> Go into Gmail, and click into Settings. Go to the Accounts and Import section and click on: <br><img class="wp-image-864" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_T3oytpBy_wzQSGpI-j-1Fg.png" alt=""><br> Enter the email address you want to forward, keep Treat As Alias checked, and on the next screen fill it out like this: <br><img class="wp-image-863" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_mSsn2VzT8QymyMq0grJWoA.png" alt=""><br>Username is your personal email address<br> If you are like me, youll get this error: <br><img class="wp-image-865" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_WfAEDhtiVqqzX1Q8tcrpPQ.png" alt=""></li><li> If you get the<strong>Less Secure Apps error</strong>, you have to go into your Security Settings in your Google Account. Google explains this more<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/6010255" target="_blank">here</a>but just follow my steps instead of reading that. The way I ended up being able to do it was by<strong>Enabling 2 Step Verification</strong>and then requesting a custom<strong>App Password</strong>. <br><img class="wp-image-866" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_9D60dZjkE9eT8NMs-EtQhA.png" alt=""></li><li> Enable 2 Step Verification by click on that setting in the<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://myaccount.google.com/security" target="_blank">Security</a>section of your Google Account and following the Steps. Be sure to have your phone nearby. </li><li> Once youve enabled 2-Step, your account wont be able to interface with Less Secure Apps with your normal password. So, go into<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://myaccount.google.com/security" target="_blank">App Passwords in your Google Account</a>, and create a custom password for your Mail client. <br><img class="wp-image-867" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1__JJ43TOjhvQ8lNbu0f0rzw.png" alt=""><br> After clicking<strong>Generate</strong>you should then get a screen like this: <br><img class="wp-image-868" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_eCPGtAu3j1JNItUwyQhymA.png" alt=""></li><li> Copy paste that password into the yellow screen back in Gmail. <br><img class="wp-image-869" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_mSsn2VzT8QymyMq0grJWoA-1.png" alt=""></li><li> Pray to your version of a higher power. </li><li> Hopefully it worked! If it did you will see this screen: <br><img class="wp-image-870" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_gTiltOEEmmmvIwIPHjFC9g.png" alt=""></li><li> Now all you need to do is click on the email link that Google just sent you to confirm your email, then you will be able to send email from your newly created forward address! <br><img class="wp-image-871" style="width: 600px;" src="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1_jeeKkBEo0kAba11l68qpLw.png" alt=""></li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://medium.com/@seanmaroni/setting-up-a-free-custom-domain-email-address-with-godaddy-and-gmail-2019-edition-d190cff0b19b">Original article</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'Setting Up Free Custom Domain Email Addresses with GoDaddy and Gmail (2019 Edition)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'setting-up-free-custom-domain-email-addresses-with-godaddy-and-gmail-2019-edition', '', '', '2019-10-16 01:14:28', '2019-10-16 01:14:28', '', 0, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/?p=845', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(846, 2, '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Recently I went into the rats nest that is GoDaddys dashboard to setup a&nbsp;<strong>free</strong>&nbsp;email forwarding address for a side project. I found it fairly impossible. Thus leads me to this post.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is how to do this in the 2019 version of GoDaddys dashboard and Gmail. It will take you about 30 minutes. Just do all the things I say and youll get out alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->\n<h1 id="057c">Here we go</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li>Visit your GoDaddy dashboard&nbsp;<a href="https://account.godaddy.com/products/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">here</a>. Go to the <a href="https://account.godaddy.com/products/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">My Products</a> section.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Scroll all the way down past your domains, and expand the&nbsp;<strong>Additional Products</strong>&nbsp;section. (this took me forever to find be grateful).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*h3BKsRTEdtiMlikSKRDPwQ.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Click on the <strong>Redeem</strong> button next to&nbsp;<strong>Email Forwarding</strong>. In the dropdown window, select the domain youd like a forwarding email address for and click the button to redeem the <strong>100 pack</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*Bu4tYqqNB0wdxdc-ytc7Sg.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Scroll up to the&nbsp;<strong>Workspace Email&nbsp;</strong>section and click on&nbsp;<strong>Options</strong>&nbsp;next to the 100 pack. Dont click on Sign It it wont work if you dont have another email with GoDaddy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*9hV5wsf7EN6T1RhnJkol7A.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Click on the hilariously tiny <strong>Launch Control Center</strong> button in the top right. Yeah, GoDaddy aint interested in you doing this in the least. They want your money not your love.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*TWM6NTEH0XTJCC-96grFcQ.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6.&nbsp;<em>[Thanks to&nbsp;</em><a href="https://medium.com/u/1b0c376ad8f?source=post_page-----d190cff0b19b----------------------" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><em>Gissel Zamonsky</em></a><em>&nbsp;for pointing this out]&nbsp;</em>Check your MX Records for this domain by clicking on&nbsp;<strong>Tools &gt; Server Settings</strong>. If youre MX Records are not yet setup (GoDaddy doesnt do it for you), navigate to your DNS settings for this domain and add the two MX records below.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*c3643BvOvLdarWE3oxTZOw.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*CNxe2S3IoM677FFJmz_2Nw.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>7. Now, once you are in the Launch Control Center click on&nbsp;<strong>Create Forward</strong>&nbsp;in the menu bar.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*Kst2pZ0jHwWlrTMjc4f8AA.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>8. Enter the email address you want to create for your domain, and enter in the Gmail email address you want to forward that email to. You may want to go ahead and enable the Catch All feature on this screen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*E-5HGv3rO5PHXTx0mMx9vw.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Great, now you should be able to send a test email to that email address. It will possibly take several minutes for your test email to actually arrive, given the rusty legacy tubes and pipes of the internet. Use this time to send GoDaddy a strongly worded email about how silly they are for making you do all of this.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you receive your test email, now it is time to setup Gmail so that you can send outgoing emails as this email address. This is a good time to close the GoDaddy browser tabs triumphantly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Google explains how to do this&nbsp;<a href="https://support.google.com/domains/answer/3251241?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">here</a>. I know you think this part will be easy, but it will not be easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>9. Go into Gmail, and click into Settings. Go to the Accounts and Import section and click on:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*T3oytpBy_wzQSGpI-j-1Fg.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enter the email address you want to forward, keep Treat As Alias checked, and on the next screen fill it out like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*mSsn2VzT8QymyMq0grJWoA.png?q=20" alt=""/><figcaption>Username is your personal gmail address</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are like me, youll get this error:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*WfAEDhtiVqqzX1Q8tcrpPQ.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>10. If you get the&nbsp;<strong>Less Secure Apps error</strong>, you have to go into your Security Settings in your Google Account. Google explains this more&nbsp;<a href="https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/6010255" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">here</a>&nbsp;but just follow my steps instead of reading that. The way I ended up being able to do it was by&nbsp;<strong>Enabling 2 Step Verification</strong>&nbsp;and then requesting a custom&nbsp;<strong>App Password</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*9D60dZjkE9eT8NMs-EtQhA.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>11. Enable 2 Step Verification by click on that setting in the&nbsp;<a href="https://myaccount.google.com/security" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Security</a>&nbsp;section of your Google Account and following the Steps. Be sure to have your phone nearby.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>12. Once youve enabled 2-Step, your account wont be able to interface with Less Secure Apps with your normal password. So, go into&nbsp;<a href="https://myaccount.google.com/security" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">App Passwords in your Google Account</a>, and create a custom password for your Mail client.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*_JJ43TOjhvQ8lNbu0f0rzw.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After clicking&nbsp;<strong>Generate</strong>&nbsp;you should then get a screen like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*eCPGtAu3j1JNItUwyQhymA.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>13. Copy paste that password into the yellow screen back in Gmail.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*mSsn2VzT8QymyMq0grJWoA.png?q=20" alt=""/><figcaption>The Username is your personal Gmail email address</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>14. Pray to your version of a higher power.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>15. Hopefully it worked! If it did you will see this screen:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*gTiltOEEmmmvIwIPHjFC9g.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>16. Now all you need to do is click on the email link that Google just sent you to confirm your email, then you will be able to send email from your newly created forward address!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/60/1*jeeKkBEo0kAba11l68qpLw.png?q=20" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '845-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '2019-10-16 00:36:26', '', 845, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/845-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
