(894, 2, '2019-10-16 04:28:51', '2019-10-16 04:28:51', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Install Oracle VM VirtualBox </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://www.oracle.com/virtualization/technologies/vm/downloads/virtualbox-downloads.html">https://www.oracle.com/virtualization/technologies/vm/downloads/virtualbox-downloads.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Follow these steps to create a virtual machine with IE10: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>1- Download Windows 7 Iso</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First of all, you need to download a&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Windows 7</strong>&nbsp;Installer with&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Iso</strong>, and&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Bootable&nbsp;</strong>formats</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/wp-content/en_windows_7_ultimate_x64_dvd.iso">Download Windows 7 ISO</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>2- Declare&nbsp; Windows 7 virtual machine</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, you need to open the&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>VirtualBox</strong>, select&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>New</strong>&nbsp;to create a new virtual machine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909264.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enter the name of virtual machine, herein called&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>"Windows7"&nbsp;</strong>by me</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909297.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Choose the number of&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>RAMs</strong>&nbsp;to be provided to the virtual machine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909379.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, create a virtual hard disk for your virtual machine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909406.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909408.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909433.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Select the position where your virtual disk file will be created and designate the size of your virtual disk.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909488.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Windows 7</strong>&nbsp;virtual machine is created and you can see it on the&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>VirtualBox Manager&nbsp;</strong>window. It is noted that your virtual machine just created is not installed operating system, therefore, you need to install an operating system for it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909540.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>3- Install operating system</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the above step, you have just declared a virtual machine on the&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>VirtualBox</strong>. Now, you need to install an operating system for it.Press&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>"Start"</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909579.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>VirtualBox</strong>&nbsp;will ask you where the ISO file downloaded by you in the previous step is.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909625.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OK, at this time, the operating system starts being installed. If you are familiar with the installation of&nbsp;<strong>windows&nbsp;</strong>operating system, this is very simple.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909712.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909741.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909785.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909818.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18909820.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910118.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enter password and hint. Your hinted information helps you remember the password if you forget it in the future.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910160.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910194.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Select time and time zone:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910245.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910247.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Windows is installed!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://o7planning.org/en/11883/cache/images/i/18910313.png" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Update to IE10</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open browser and visit:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-ca/download/details.aspx?id=39232">https://www.microsoft.com/en-ca/download/details.aspx?id=39232</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click the "click here to download manually" and then install the exe </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Install Oracle VM VirtualBox for IE10', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '883-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-16 04:28:51', '2019-10-16 04:28:51', '', 883, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/883-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(895, 2, '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>apt-get install dos2unix</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then use it like so:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>dos2unix /var/www/project-create.sh</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'Install DOS to Unix converter', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'install-dos-to-unix-converter', '', '', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '', 0, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/?p=895', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(896, 2, '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>apt-get install dos2unix</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then use it like so:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>dos2unix /var/www/project-create.sh</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'Install DOS to Unix converter', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '895-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '2019-10-16 17:04:56', '', 895, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/895-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(897, 2, '2019-10-17 04:10:58', '2019-10-17 04:10:58', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Three steps to configure the deployment process:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1750/1*sepbx-OJjGU3ya_VRVOUIA.jpeg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><li> <strong>Create an empty Git repo</strong>&nbsp;on the server </li><li> <strong>Write a Git Hook</strong>&nbsp;to deploy the code </li><li> <strong>Deploy</strong>&nbsp;from the local computer </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>On the remote server</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Add two files project-create.sh and project-delete.sh to /www directory</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>project-create.sh:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>#!/bin/bash\n\n# source: https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/58cabf43c2977e48ef0804848dee46c3\n# and another script to delete the directories created by this script\n# project-delete.sh: https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/e28069c18ebe8f3244f8e4bf2af6b2cb\n\n# Call this file with `bash ./project-create.sh project-name [service-name]`\n# - project-name is mandatory\n# - service-name is optional\n\n# This will creates 4 directories and a git `post-receive` hook.\n# The 4 directories are:\n# - $GIT: a git repo\n# - $TMP: a temporary directory for deployment\n# - $WWW: a directory for the actual production files\n# - $ENV: a directory for the env variables\n\n# When you push your code to the git repo,\n# the `post-receive` hook will deploy the code\n# in the $TMP directory, then copy it to $WWW.\n\nDIR_TMP="/var/tmp/"\nDIR_WWW="/var/www/"\nDIR_GIT="/var/git/"\nDIR_ENV="/var/env/"\nDIR_HTML="/public_html"\n\nif [ $# -eq 0 ]; then\n	echo \'No project name provided (mandatory)\'\n	exit 1\nelse\n	echo "- Project name:" "$1"\nfi\n\nif [ -z "$2" ]; then\n	echo \'- Service name (optional): not provided\'\n	GIT=$DIR_GIT$1.git\n	TMP=$DIR_TMP$1\n	WWW=$DIR_WWW$1$DIR_HTML\n	ENV=$DIR_ENV$1\n	\n	# Create $WWW parent directory\n	sudo mkdir -p "$DIR_WWW$1$DIR_HTML"\n	cd "$DIR_WWW"\n	sudo chown -R www-data:www-data "$1"\n	sudo chmod -R g+rwX "$1"\nelse\n	echo "- Service name (optional):" "$2"\n	GIT=$DIR_GIT$1.$2.git\n	TMP=$DIR_TMP$1.$2\n	WWW=$DIR_WWW$1$DIR_HTML/$2\n	ENV=$DIR_ENV$1/$2\nfi\n\necho "- git:" "$GIT"\necho "- tmp:" "$TMP"\necho "- www:" "$WWW"\necho "- env:" "$ENV"\n\nexport GIT\nexport TMP\nexport WWW\nexport ENV\n\n# Create a directory for the env repository\nsudo mkdir -p "$ENV"\ncd "$ENV" || exit\nsudo touch .env\n\n# Create a directory for the git repository\nsudo mkdir -p "$GIT"\ncd "$GIT" || exit\n\n# Init the repo as an empty git repository\nsudo git init --bare\n\n# Define group recursively to "www-data", on the directories\nsudo chgrp -R www-data .\n\n# Define permissions recursively, on the sub-directories\n# g = group, + add rights, r = read, w = write, X = directories only\n# . = curent directory as a reference\nsudo chmod -R g+rwX .\n\n# Sets the setgid bit on all the directories\n# https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/Directory-Setuid-and-Setgid.html\nsudo find . -type d -exec chmod g+s \'{}\' +\n\n# Make the directory a shared repo\nsudo git config core.sharedRepository group\n\ncd hooks || exit\n\n# create a post-receive file\nsudo tee post-receive &lt;&lt;EOF\n#!/bin/bash\n# The production directory\nWWW="${WWW}"\n# A temporary directory for deployment\nTMP="${TMP}"\n# The Git repo\nGIT="${GIT}"\n# The Env  repo\nENV="${ENV}"\n# Deploy the content to the temporary directory\nmkdir -p \\$TMP\ngit --work-tree=\\$TMP --git-dir=\\$GIT checkout -f\n# Copy the env variable to the temporary directory\ncp -a \\$ENV/. \\$TMP\n# Do stuffs, like npm install\ncd \\$TMP || exit\n# Replace the content of the production directory\n# with the temporary directory\ncd / || exit\nrm -rf \\$WWW\nmv \\$TMP \\$WWW\n# Do stuff like starting docker\ncd \\$WWW || exit\n# docker-compose up -d --build\nEOF\n\n# make it executable\nsudo chmod +x post-receive</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Above is an edited copy made for my server. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gist:  <a href="https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/58cabf43c2977e48ef0804848dee46c3">https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/58cabf43c2977e48ef0804848dee46c3</a> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>project-delete.sh: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>#!/bin/bash\n\n# source: https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/e28069c18ebe8f3244f8e4bf2af6b2cb\n# and another script to create the directories deleted by this script\n# project-create.sh: https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/58cabf43c2977e48ef0804848dee46c3\n\n# Call this file with `bash ./project-delete.sh project-name [service-name]`\n# - project-name is mandatory\n# - service-name is optional\n\n# This will delete 4 directories\n# - $GIT: a git repo\n# - $TMP: a temporary directory for deployment\n# - $WWW: a directory for the actual production files\n# - $ENV: a directory for the env variables\n\nDIR_TMP="/var/tmp/"\nDIR_WWW="/var/www/"\nDIR_GIT="/var/git/"\nDIR_ENV="/var/env/"\n\nfunction dir_delete() {\n        sudo rm -rf "$1"\n}\n\nif [ $# -eq 0 ]; then\n        echo \'No project name provided (mandatory)\'\n        exit 1\nelse\n        echo "- Project name:" "$1"\nfi\n\nif [ -z "$2" ]; then\n        echo \'- Service name (optional): not provided\'\n        GIT=$DIR_GIT$1.git\n        TMP=$DIR_TMP$1\n        WWW=$DIR_WWW$1\n        ENV=$DIR_ENV$1\nelse\n        echo "- Service name (optional):" "$2"\n        GIT=$DIR_GIT$1.$2.git\n        TMP=$DIR_TMP$1.$2\n        WWW=$DIR_WWW$1/$2\n        ENV=$DIR_ENV$1/$2\nfi\n\necho "- git:" "$GIT"\necho "- tmp:" "$TMP"\necho "- www:" "$WWW"\necho "- env:" "$ENV"\n\ndir_delete "$GIT"\ndir_delete "$ENV"\ndir_delete "$WWW"\ndir_delete "$TMP"</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gist:  <a href="https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/e28069c18ebe8f3244f8e4bf2af6b2cb">https://gist.github.com/francoisromain/e28069c18ebe8f3244f8e4bf2af6b2cb</a> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Update both files to be unix encoded:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>dos2unix /var/www/project-create.sh\ndos2unix /var/www/project-delete.sh</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Before executing the file, lets check a few things.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check members of group www-data:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>grep \'www-data\' /etc/group</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If user you\'ll use on Git (the ssh key you need to load) is not part of group, then add like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>usermod -a -G www-data christine</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Create a new project on the server:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>bash /var/www/project-create.sh &lt;your-project></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Change the directory owner and group (having chris as the user breaks keeps christine user blocked out):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>sudo chown www-data:www-data /var/www</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>On your local computer</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Bitbucket create a new repo as usual. Clone it to a new project folder under sites. Add a test file and commit it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open the Git terminal now and write this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code># Add your server as a Git remote called \'deploy\'\ngit remote add deploy ssh://christine@35.192.41.230/var/git/&lt;your-project>.git/\n\n# Push your code and deploy\ngit push deploy master</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Change remote url if things changed:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>git remote set-url deploy ssh://chris@35.192.41.230/var/git/&lt;your-project>.git/\ngit remote set-url deploy https://github.com/USERNAME/REPOSITORY.git</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Add SSH key to Git</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code># Lists already added identities (ssh keys)\nssh-add -l\n\n#Run SSH Agent\neval `ssh-agent -s`\n\n# Add a new identity (you\'ll see name of file when you showed the list)\nssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa\n#Password is 57575757aA</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open id_rsa.pub under C:\\Users\\Christine.ssh. Check Google Compute under Metadata to see if this SSH key has been added already. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note: Trying to load ppk files didn\'t work.. I\'d create new ones and I couldn\'t get past the password when trying to add them to Git. Think Git will only accept id_rsa.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Getting error:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Okay now Git says its moved but I don\'t see that on the server!!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Look into these:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://help.github.com/en/articles/changing-a-remotes-url">https://help.github.com/en/articles/changing-a-remotes-url</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://github.com/facebookresearch/deepmask/issues/23">https://github.com/facebookresearch/deepmask/issues/23</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Bitbucket-questions/Permission-denied-publickey-fatal-Could-not-read-from-remote/qaq-p/448733">https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Bitbucket-questions/Permission-denied-publickey-fatal-Could-not-read-from-remote/qaq-p/448733</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class="wp-block-button"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="https://medium.com/@francoisromain/vps-deploy-with-git-fea605f1303b">Original article</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->', 'Deploy a website to a remote server with Git push', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'deploy-a-website-to-a-remote-server-with-git-push', '', '', '2019-10-17 16:45:08', '2019-10-17 16:45:08', '', 0, 'http://wiki.christinewilson.ca/?p=897', 0, 'post', '', 0),
